\details{
Formula random effects in \code{\link[=JAGS_formula]{JAGS_formula()}} and \code{\link[=JAGS_fit]{JAGS_fit()}} require an
explicit \code{prior_random()} object. The top-level arguments are defaults used
by every random-effect block unless a named \code{random_block()} override is
supplied in \code{...}.

Each override name must match a stable random-effect block label generated
from the formula parser or supplied by the user through named random terms.
This keeps prior specification separate from formula syntax. For example,
if the formula contains a block named \code{"study"}, then
\code{prior_random(study = random_block(...))} overrides only that block.

\code{random_term()} is an alias of \code{random_block()} retained for readability in
user-facing code.
}
\section{Standard-deviation priors}{

\code{sd} must be a BayesTools prior object with nonnegative support, such as a
truncated normal, gamma, point prior at zero, or mixture prior. When a
structure needs multiple marginal standard deviations, a single \code{sd} prior is
replicated over those SD components unless a more specific override is
supplied by the random-effect resolver.

For ordinary estimation, use continuous positive SD priors. Use point or
mixture priors at zero only when a random-effect component is intentionally
fixed or model-averaged.
}

\section{Covariance structures}{

\code{random_covariance()} stores structure-specific covariance settings.
Supported structure labels are:
\itemize{
\item \code{"ID"}: independent columns with one shared SD.
\item \code{"DIAG"}: independent columns with one SD per generated column.
\item \code{"CS"} / \code{"HCS"}: compound symmetry over one or more index variables,
with one scalar correlation \code{rho}; \code{"HCS"} has one SD per index level.
Multiple index variables in \code{cs(index1 + index2 | group)} are combined
with \code{interaction(..., drop = TRUE)}.
\item \code{"AR"} / \code{"AR1"} / \code{"HAR"}: discrete autoregressive structure over a
single ordered index variable, with one scalar correlation \code{rho}; \code{"HAR"}
has one SD per index level.
\item \code{"CAR"}: continuous-time AR(1), currently for \code{car(time | group)},
using \code{rho ^ abs(t_i - t_j)} with \verb{0 < rho < 1}.
\item \code{"UN"} / \code{"US"}: unstructured covariance with SD priors and \code{prior_lkj()}.
}

The formula parser owns the actual structure used by a block. Supplying a
conflicting \code{structure} in \code{random_covariance()} is rejected when the formula
is resolved.
}

\section{Correlation priors}{

Use \code{prior_lkj(eta = ...)} for full unstructured correlation matrices. The
compiled JAGS backend is used by default, with a syntax fallback available
through \code{backend = "syntax"}.

Use \code{rho} for scalar-correlation structures (\code{"CS"}, \code{"HCS"}, \code{"AR"},
\code{"HAR"}, and \code{"CAR"}). \code{rho_scale} controls the scale on which the prior is
placed:
\itemize{
\item \code{"fisher_z"} places the prior on \code{atanh(rho)} and is the default. A point
prior at zero corresponds to independence. For one-sided structures such
as \code{"CAR"}, the Fisher-z prior is truncated to the valid raw-rho interval.
\item \code{"logit"} places the prior on a logit transform of the valid raw-rho
interval.
\item \code{"rho"} places the prior directly on raw \code{rho}; the prior is truncated to
the structure-specific valid interval.
}
}

\section{Variance allocation}{

\code{random_variance_allocation()} expresses one total SD prior plus a Dirichlet
prior over variance fractions. Multiple named allocations can be supplied in
\code{prior_random()}; child allocations can inherit one component of an earlier
allocation through \code{parent = allocation_ref(...)}.

\deqn{\sigma_j = \sigma_{\mathrm{total}}\sqrt{w_j}, \quad
      w \sim \mathrm{Dirichlet}(\alpha).}

This is useful for nested or crossed random intercepts when the prior should
control total heterogeneity separately from how that heterogeneity is
allocated across components. The allocation targets named random-effect
blocks through \code{terms}. If \code{terms = NULL}, the allocation targets all
remaining unallocated random-effect blocks at resolution time. Generated JAGS
syntax supports allocated blocks with one SD component, homogeneous
structures where one SD controls the block, and explicit \code{components = "sd"}
allocations that split the resolved SD leaves of one heterogeneous block.
Use \code{scale = "total_variance"} to preserve summed variance and
\code{scale = "mean_variance"} to preserve average variance inside a
heterogeneous block.
}

\section{Monitoring and prediction}{

\code{random_monitor()} controls which random-effect quantities are saved from
JAGS. The default monitors standardized latent random effects because they
are required for bridge sampling and for reconstructing group-level
coefficients in prediction. Turning \code{latent = FALSE} can reduce memory use,
but bridge sampling and conditional prediction may require refitting.

\code{random_new_levels()} is reserved for future prediction support for new
grouping levels. It currently requires \code{allow = FALSE}.
}

\examples{
sd_prior <- prior(
  "normal", list(mean = 0, sd = 0.5),
  truncation = list(lower = 0, upper = Inf)
)
rho_prior <- prior("normal", list(mean = 0, sd = 0.5))

# One SD prior used for every random-effect block.
prior_random(sd = sd_prior)

# Override a named block while keeping a global default.
prior_random(
  sd = sd_prior,
  study = random_block(sd = prior("gamma", list(shape = 2, rate = 2)))
)

# Unstructured covariance: SD prior plus LKJ correlation prior.
prior_random(
  study = random_term(
    covariance = random_covariance(
      structure = "UN",
      sd = sd_prior,
      cor = prior_lkj(eta = 2)
    )
  )
)

# Scalar-rho structure with a Fisher-z prior.
prior_random(
  study_time = random_term(
    covariance = random_covariance(
      structure = "AR",
      sd = sd_prior,
      rho = rho_prior,
      rho_scale = "fisher_z"
    )
  )
)

# Total SD plus Dirichlet variance allocation.
prior_random(
  random_variance_allocation(
    terms = c("study", "drug"),
    sd = sd_prior,
    allocation = prior("dirichlet", list(alpha = c(1, 1)))
  )
)

# A child allocation can split one inherited variance budget.
prior_random(
  random_variance_allocation(
    name = "total_re",
    terms = c(nested = "nested", simple = "study"),
    sd = sd_prior,
    allocation = prior("dirichlet", list(alpha = c(1, 1)))
  ),
  random_variance_allocation(
    name = "nested_split",
    parent = allocation_ref("total_re", "nested"),
    terms = c("paper", "country"),
    allocation = prior("dirichlet", list(alpha = c(3, 1)))
  )
)
}
